## Problem1('36')

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a = random(2,5,1);
$b = random(2,5,1);

$c = "0^{+}";
$f = "(1 + $a x)^{$b/x}";

$num = "$b \ln(1 + $a x)";
$den = "x";

$dnum = "\frac{$b}{1+$a x} \cdot $a";
$dden = "1";

$ba = $b*$a;

$ans = "e^($ba)";


TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_TEXT
Evaluate the limit, using L'H\{ MODES(HTML=>"&ocirc;",TeX=>"\^o") \}pital's Rule. 
$BR
Enter $BBOLD INF $EBOLD for \(\infty\), $BBOLD -INF $EBOLD 
for \(-\infty\), or $BBOLD DNE $EBOLD if the limit does not exist,
but is neither \(\infty\) nor \(-\infty\).
$PAR
\( \displaystyle 
  \lim_{x\to $c} $f =
\) \{ans_rule(10) \}
END_TEXT

ANS(Compute($ans)->cmp());

Context()->normalStrings;
BEGIN_SOLUTION
First use the property \(f(x) = e^{\ln f(x)}\) and
laws of logarithms to
re-express the function as
a fraction.  
\[ 
   $f = e^{\ln $f} = e^{ ($b/x) \ln(1 + $a x)},
\]
and
\[
  ($b/x) \ln (1 + $a x) = \dfrac{$b\ln (1 + $a x)}{x}.
\]
Find the limit of this part (using L'H\{ MODES(HTML=>"&ocirc;",TeX=>"\^o") \}pital's Rule).
\[
  \lim_{x \to $c} \frac{$num}{$den}
  = \lim_{x \to $c} \frac{$dnum}{$dden}
  = \lim_{x \to $c} 
  \dfrac{$ba}{1+$a x} = $ba.
\]
Then plug this result back in to find the original limit.
\[
  = \lim_{x \to $c} $f
  = e^{\lim_{x \to $c} \ln $f}
  = e^{$ba}.
\]
END_SOLUTION

